# Issue commit linking

Every **task-related** commit must reference the linked GitHub issue (`#N`) so the **Development** panel links correctly and the issue auto-closes on merge to `main`. **Resolve `#N` from Linear** before committing (`get_issue("PW-N")` → GitHub attachment URL or title).

## Resolving `#N` from Linear

Task work uses **`PW-N`** everywhere except git. At commit time only:

1. `get_issue("PW-N")` → read `attachments[]` for GitHub issue URL, or parse `#N` from title if synced.
2. Use that `#N` in subject `[#N]` and body `fixes #N` — never `fixes PW-N`.

Orchestrator execution prompts include a **COMMIT LINK** block with pre-resolved `#N` when available.

## Required subject format

```
<type>(<scope>)[#N]: <imperative summary>
```

| Part | Rule |
|---|---|
| `<type>` | Conventional Commits: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `ci`, `build`, `perf` |
| `<scope>` | Allowed scopes from `01-git-workflow.mdc` |
| `[#N]` | **Mandatory** on task commits |
| Summary | Imperative mood; whole subject ≤72 chars |

## Required body format

```
fixes #N
```

Place on its own line in the commit body. Multiple issues: one per line.

## Epic (parent Feature) issues

When a task is a **child of an epic** (orchestrator passes `PARENT: #<epic>`):

| Commit | Subject | Body |
|---|---|---|
| Any subtask under epic P | `[#<leaf>][#<P>]` | `fixes #<leaf>` + `refs #<P>` |
| **Final** child of epic P | `[#<leaf>][#<P>]` | `fixes #<leaf>` + `refs #<P>` + `fixes #<P>` when P is in `CLOSE_PARENTS` |
| Atomic leaf (no parent) | `[#<leaf>]` | `fixes #<leaf>` |

**Epic linkage vs epic close:**

- **`[#<epic>]` in subject** and **`refs #<epic>` in body** on **every** subtask commit — links all child commits to the epic in the Development panel without auto-closing the epic on merge to `main`.
- **`fixes #<epic>`** only on the **final** in-scope child — orchestrator supplies parent(s) in `CLOSE_PARENTS`; execution agents must not guess.

**Do not** put `fixes #<epic>` on intermediate subtasks — that auto-closes the epic when the first subtask lands on `main`.

Subject ≤72 chars: include both `[#<leaf>]` and `[#<epic>]`; shorten the summary if needed.

Orchestrator passes `PARENT: #P`, `CLOSE_PARENTS: [#P, …]` or `none` in execution prompts. Execution agents **must not guess**.

## Examples

```bash
# GOOD — intermediate subtask under epic #8
feat(auth)[#11][#8]: add GitHub OAuth callback handler

fixes #11
refs #8

# GOOD — last in-scope child of epic #8
feat(auth)[#12][#8]: add refresh token rotation

fixes #12
refs #8
fixes #8

# BAD — subtask missing epic linkage
feat(auth)[#11]: add GitHub OAuth callback handler

fixes #11

# BAD — premature epic close on intermediate subtask
feat(auth)[#11][#8]: add OAuth callback

fixes #11
fixes #8
```

## Auto-close on merge

GitHub auto-closes issues with `fixes #N` in commit body when merged to `main` (default branch).

## Exceptions (no issue key required)

- Pure repo hygiene: `chore(repo): init pnpm workspace` (rare)
- Integration merge commits: `chore(repo)[#N]: integrate orchestrator batch (<BATCH_ID>)`
